commentBody:
@Francis

I don't.

Mostly because I don't know who he is :D

@Andrzej

I think he's worth looking up.  I find his "Pitch meeting" series to be hilarious, where he does a sketch in which a writer is pitching a movie to a producer.

Of course it leans heavily on all the plot holes in the movie.

@Cindy

Too close syndrome. A phrase invented by fellow commentator Steve L to indicate that one someone has professional or personal experience in a subject, they'll object to clueing that would seem perfectly acceptable to a lay person.

In my case, I was an avid chess player in my youth and am an even more avid diner in my adulthood

@Barry Ancona et al

Charcuterie does refer to the meats, but in the US a charcuterie board usually includes an array of cheeses, fruits, nuts and crackers. A soft cheese like Brie could be used as a spread for the crackers. And because it’s on the board, you might call it a charcuterie spread.

I’ll allow it.

@Francis
I’m sure you know this but you can redeem Gold Stars. Once solved you click “redeem” on the Info menu. $7.99 per puzzle (up from $6.99 on 2025 puzzles). 

Not going to retire on my puzzle earnings but it gets me a cup of coffee and a scone. Better than nothing 🤷🏻‍♂️

@Striker

I feel my leg being tugged on with great vigor, but I can't quite tell.  

If it is a gotcha, it's really, really well done.  The detail really sells it.

@Francis

😂 Just a friendly “how ya doin” in the form of a gentle leg tug. 

Wouldn’t it be nice though!

@Wyra

What Lucky said. I usually start the night before so have plenty of simmering and can still keep my streak, if I care, which I don’t.
By the way, don’t know if you saw my late post the other day but appreciated the Kingdom Come recommendation, it’s a great game and I enjoyed it!

@Times Rita

I never knew Miro's gender from the name.

As for Maria - it's quite common as a second name for Catholics. Personally, I've always found it very strange. And it's only ever Maria, never Louise, Anna or Rita :)

@Andrzej

I didn't know about cakesicles, either, and I find it almost impossible to type, so stupid is it.   Cakesicles just sounds too much like something I'd expect at a bachelorette party.

Mont-Saint-Michel looks incredible.  If I could lucid dream, I'd visit there often.

@Andrzej

It's fine.

They'll show up as comments 473-5 tomorrow morning.

@Heidi

When it comes to answers like SPA one, I just fill in three letters and wait for the crosses for the rest. 

In general, it’s a better strategy to solve puzzles in order of certainty and not by filling things in in order, or by only entering complete answers. When you hit the crosses, those filled-in letters are a help and not a hindrance.

@dutchiris

I needed ten of the 'easy mode' clues.  So you had less trouble than I did.  Not sure I could have solved it without the help.
(And I didn't want to sweat that hard, to see if I could. Places to go, other puzzles to solve...)  At least I got the longest phrases on my own, and I found today's efforts mostly enjoyable.

@Frankie B 

I didn't have any trouble with it, and I've always been kind of a mediocre solver, especially when it comes to speed.

We all have different strenghts and weaknesses, I guess. One of my weaknesses is an ignorance of trivia concerning "boy bands," probably because I'm not a member of their target audience, and a lot of what answers I'm able to get concerning sports  come solely from doing these puzzles.

@Lewis

The 5 was simply a random number. It was raised to the “spades” power. Perhaps there might have been a better choice than 5.

Had I been able to figure out a method, the rendering would have been better. I ended up using HTML encoding, which sometime works as expected in posts.

@Lewis

I am always eager to hear from anyone who likes "2001: A Space Odyssey".

It is probably my favorite of all time.

@Barry Ancona

This week's late-week puzzles are perfect examples for your "swing" Wednesday, IMHO. 

Yesterday's was fun, and I always appreciate puzzles by its constructors, but left me wondering if I'd misread the calendar! I'm with @Xword Junkie (and you, among others) about the cluing today.

@Linda Jo
In general, yes, I think new solvers like me are suspicious of any easy looking clue in a late week puzzle. Like today the Addams thing wouldn’t be wife (and I have no idea who the Addamses are/were).
In this one specifically I know who Blackpink are, so I just thought it was a very easy clue for a Friday, as several of todays were.

@Tony

There's only one thing better than Brie--Camembert!

Must be "ripe." And where's the baguette?

@Jonathan Guss "biceps - is actually singular; the plural is bicepses. (I kid you not!)"

In fact, the plural is "bicipites."

Now, go tell that to the gorilla with the 18" guns, curling 45kgs on the preacher bench.

@Steve L

Right. You give them access to your NYT account.

I find that invasive.

@Steve L

They are both believed to be from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrḗǵʰ-s if you go back far enough.

But if you have to go back to protolanguages, that's not sharing much of an etymology.
